      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Dreamingness wrote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />Game mechanics that make it harder on the gold sellers typically wind up making it harder on the players. Please don't make us suffer for the transgressions of those people who value money above all else. Please allow us <i>some</i> comfort in playing the game we paid you for. Thank you for listening, if you are. </div></div> <br /> <br />I couldn't agree more. I see this in the world all over. More often than not those that don't do the &quot;bad&quot; thing (even when the thing is bad like with crimes) get punished while the people actually committing the act get to keep on doing their thing. <br /> <br />We no longer get to have an Auction House or Mailboxes because it makes it too easy for the gold sellers. Well, they are still making money and we're getting annoyed more and more each day over the limited way in which we get to play our game.  <br /> <br />The gold sellers <i>are not</i> being punished. We are. <br /> <br />For example, living in California it is actually easier even allows one to be closer to free to be a criminal. The barrage of law after law we get here has made it a desirable thing to be a &quot;criminal&quot; (which is more and more becoming just a label). I'm not for crime and actual criminals are gross to me. But it makes you wonder, one day when eating red meat or playing the guitar is a crime who's really going to care if they are labeled as a &quot;criminal&quot;? It wouldn't actually be true. If someone called me an apple, it wouldn't make it true... <br /> <br />I know that I'm going a little far on this, but when you see it day after day it just feels good to finally talk about it and see someone else notices it too.</div>
