      <div class="msgContentFrame">While I agree that banning people who buy gil is appropriate, as it causes bots to go out and cause problems to players, I cannot place all the blame on RMT groups or players that do it. <br /> <br />Instead, the problem lies with the game. I can tell you, I would easily pay someone to level my damn crafting skills, considering that doing it myself feels just like my day job. I go to work in the morning. I return home, only to sit behind a desk again and watch someone else sit behind the desk work. And click 'standard' every 10 seconds. That's precious free time wasted, and if I can pay someone to get me to 40, I would honestly have to consider it. <br /> <br />'You dont like crafting, don't craft' <br /> <br />I don't like running around all day looking for repairs either. <br /> <br /> <br />TLDR + Solution: Make the game fun, and it will be a lot easier to limit RMT. It's always gonna be there to some extent, but if people are less inclined to do it, it will not become problematic. <br /> <br /> <br />One suggestion would be to make a craft leveling system similar to that of eve online. Train while you're offline.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div> <br /><img src="http://common.zam.com/xivsigs/1815197.png" alt="Signature Image" border="0" /> <br /></div></div>
